The shareholders of publicly traded hedge fund management firm Sculptor Cap=
ital Management Inc. have a choice between two options:
=09Sculptor has signed a merger agreement to sell itself to Rithm Capital C=
orp. for $11.15 per share. It is asking shareholders to approve that deal. =
If they vote yes, then they will almost certainly get cashed out at $11.15 =
per share.
  [1]

=09Somebody else has offered to buy Sculptor for $12.76 per share. Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s board of directors says that this offer is too risky: Its financ=
ing is=C2=A0uncertain, and this offer (like Rithm=E2=80=99s) is conditional=
 on at least a majority of Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fund=C2=A0clients=C2=A0=
approving the new owner.=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s board says that the client=
s might not=C2=A0approve the new owner, in which case the $12.76 deal would=
 fall apart and shareholders would be left with nothing.
  [2]



They get to pick between a pretty certain $11.15 per share and a riskier $1=
2.76 per share. Sculptor=E2=80=99s board wants them to pick the safer $11.1=
5. Last Thursday, Sculptor  filed a revised proxy statement, again making t=
he case for the $11.15 Rithm deal.
We have   talked   about this   deal a   lot around   here. I am being cute=
, saying that =E2=80=9Csomebody else=E2=80=9D is bidding $12.76. I know who=
 it is, and so do you probably.=C2=A0It has been   widely reported in the m=
edia. It=E2=80=99s a group led by Boaz Weinstein of Saba Capital Management=
 and including his buddies Bill Ackman (Pershing Square Capital Management)=
, Marc Lasry (Avenue Capital Management) and Jeff Yass (Susquehanna Interna=
tional Group).
But Sculptor is also being cute. Its revised  proxy statement on Thursday d=
oes not name Weinstein, Ackman, Lasry, Yass or their firms. It calls them =
=E2=80=9Ca consortium of bidders led by the founder of Bidder J,=E2=80=9D a=
nd=C2=A0a footnote to that description explains:
The Company is party to a customary NDA [nondisclosure agreement] with Bidd=
er J, entered into on December 21, 2022, that prohibits the Company from pu=
blicly disclosing the identity of Bidder J or any members of the Consortium=
. All NDAs entered into by the Company with other potential acquirers inclu=
de a similar prohibition.
I mean, sure. There is an NDA, which prohibits Weinstein from making a publ=
ic bid for Sculptor, and which technically does prohibit Sculptor from iden=
tifying Weinstein. But either side can waive the NDA. Actually Sculptor=C2=
=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0waive Weinstein=E2=80=99s NDA; the merger agreement w=
ith Rithm   prohibits it from waiving Weinstein=E2=80=99s NDA.
  [3]
=C2=A0But Weinstein can waive Rithm=E2=80=99s obligations, and presumably=
=C2=A0wants to:=C2=A0He wants his bid for Sculptor to be public,=C2=A0he=C2=
=A0can't make it public, but Sculptor can, in its proxy statement. If Sculp=
tor asked Weinstein =E2=80=9Chey I know we have an NDA but can we mention y=
our name in our proxy so that shareholders can be fully informed about the =
situation,=E2=80=9D presumably he would=C2=A0say yes.
That is what is weird here. Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders have to vote on=
 the future of the company; in some loose sense, they have to choose betwee=
n a safe deal at $11.15 and a riskier one at $12.76. Strictly speaking, tha=
t=E2=80=99s not quite true: Their actual choice =E2=80=94=C2=A0the thing th=
ey are actually voting on =E2=80=94=C2=A0is between accepting the $11.15 de=
al and=C2=A0not accepting it.=C2=A0If they vote down the Rithm deal then th=
e board might go back and get them Weinstein=E2=80=99s $12.76 deal, or a di=
fferent deal with Weinstein, or a different deal with Rithm, or a different=
 deal with a third bidder, or no deal at all.
But their rough practical choice is between taking Rithm=E2=80=99s safe dea=
l and chasing Weinstein=E2=80=99s risky deal. And Sculptor has sent them a =
proxy statement to inform their vote, which lays out all of the details of =
Rithm=E2=80=99s safe deal. But it is weirdly coy about Weinstein=E2=80=99s =
riskier deal. It summarizes Weinstein=E2=80=99s proposals and the board=E2=
=80=99s concerns, but it does not actually quote Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid or=
 give any details. It doesn=E2=80=99t even name Weinstein or his friends. I=
t is hard for shareholders to make an informed choice if you don't tell the=
m their options.
Also, I mean. Sculptor=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock closed at $12.02 on Friday. Tha=
t suggests that shareholders are not choosing the Rithm deal
  [4]
:
=09If you paid $12.02 for Sculptor stock last week, you are not hoping to s=
ell=C2=A0it for $11.15.=09If you think that $11.15 is a good price for Scul=
ptor stock and Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid is hopeless, you should not hold on =
to your stock and vote for the $11.15 Rithm deal. You should sell the stock=
 now for $12.02!=C2=A0

If I were Sculptor=E2=80=99s board of directors, this would=C2=A0worry=C2=
=A0me. If I really thought that the Weinstein deal was too risky and that R=
ithm was the way to go, I would be concerned that the shareholders don=E2=
=80=99t seem to believe that. I=E2=80=99d want the proxy to be really clear=
 about the problems with Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid, and about why it would ne=
ver work. I=E2=80=99d want to at least name him!
Anyway, as we have discussed a lot, Sculptor's board sees two main problems=
 with Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid. One is about the financing. The board has ra=
ised various complaints about the contingency and inadequacy of the financi=
ng, and Weinstein and friends have kept answering those complaints by putti=
ng up more money, and Sculptor has kept finding new complaints. The latest =
proposal from Weinstein, on Aug. 31, provides =E2=80=9Cthat=C2=A0the $743 m=
illion of financial obligations of its newly-formed shell entity would be g=
uaranteed by a single member of the Consortium,=E2=80=9D but Sculptor objec=
ts that =E2=80=9Cthe proposed form of guarantee was not a standard uncondit=
ional guarantee to fund all obligations of the Consortium buyer when and as=
