      NAV loans
   =20
 =20

One way to think about it is that a private equity firm is a conglomerate p=
lus financial engineering. Traditionally, a conglomerate is a big company t=
hat owns lots of more-or-less unrelated businesses. Some of them will do we=
ll and others will do poorly, but the ones that are doing well can help sup=
port the ones that are doing poorly, and hopefully most will do well and th=
e overall company will make money. Meanwhile the overall company is big and=
 fairly stable (its bets are diversified), so it can borrow money cheaply, =
and it has talented managers who can make all of the component businesses w=
ork better.
A private equity=C2=A0fund also buys lots of more-or-less unrelated busines=
ses, some of which will do well and others poorly. The overall fund has tal=
ented managers who can supervise and optimize all of the businesses. But in=
stead of borrowing money at the overall fund level, the=C2=A0fund keeps eac=
h of its unrelated businesses separate as a legal and financial matter: Eac=
h business has its own balance sheet and borrows its own money. And the bus=
inesses borrow a=C2=A0lot=C2=A0of money: Private equity companies=C2=A0tend=
 to run at higher leverage than traditional public conglomerates.
  [9]

The result of this is that the PE fund is a series of somewhat independent =
bets on different businesses, and each bet has high variance: There is some=
 chance that the bet will go to zero (the company is very levered, it fails=
, and the PE fund loses its entire investment), and some chance that the be=
t will return 1,000% (the company is very levered, it succeeds, and the PE =
fund gets back 10x its=C2=A0equity investment). Whereas in a traditional co=
nglomerate the bets have less variance and are more likely to cancel each o=
ther out: Losses at one business are a drag on the other businesses in a wa=
y that isn=E2=80=99t exactly true for a PE=C2=A0fund full of independent ba=
nkruptcy-remote companies.
  [10]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA basket of options is worth more than an option on a basket=
,=E2=80=9D   I sometimes say; a PE fund is more like a basket of options, w=
hile a conglomerate where all the businesses support one another is more li=
ke an option on a basket.
On the other hand, once you own a bunch of companies you don=E2=80=99t actu=
ally want to give up on the ones that are=C2=A0struggling. The  Financial T=
imes reported last week:

Private equity firms have started to borrow against their funds to backstop=
 overly indebted portfolio companies, a new financial engineering tactic me=
ant to cope with higher interest rates and a slowdown in dealmaking.
The manoeuvres, which lenders have dubbed =E2=80=9Cdefending the portfolio=
=E2=80=9D, have cropped up as many older private equity funds run low on ca=
sh just as the companies they own struggle with their own debt loads.
Buyout firms have turned to so-called net asset value (NAV) loans, which us=
e a fund=E2=80=99s investment assets as collateral. They are deploying the =
proceeds to help pay down the debts of individual companies held by the fun=
d, according to private equity executives and senior bankers and lenders to=
 the industry.
By securing a loan against a larger pool of assets, private equity firms ar=
e able to negotiate lower borrowing costs than would be possible if the por=
tfolio company attempted to obtain a loan on its own.
Last month Vista Equity Partners, a private equity investor focused on the =
technology industry, used a NAV loan against one of its funds to help raise=
 $1bn that it then pumped into financial technology company Finastra, accor=
ding to five people familiar with the matter.

Limited liability at the company level is an essential part of the private =
equity model
  [11]
: You borrow a lot at every company, and the ones that don=E2=80=99t work o=
ut you cut loose; their creditors take losses so you can protect the rest o=
f your portfolio. But in practice you will be tempted not to cut any compan=
ies loose, to use the winners to prop up the losers and try to rescue them.

