, in three years you can hand them back a student with, say, a 50% chance o=
f getting into Harvard. This is a service that a lot of people want, and th=
at not a lot of people can provide. How should you price it?=C2=A0
One answer might be =E2=80=9Ccharge a whole lot, and then sell it to as man=
y people as can afford to pay.=E2=80=9D Another=C2=A0answer might be =E2=80=
=9Cprice discriminate as much as possible=E2=80=9D: Get the parents=E2=80=
=99 financial information, charge the really rich ones $5 million, charge l=
ess rich ones less, and do some pro bono consulting for poor but worthy can=
didates.
But there is a flaw with these answers. The more of this service you sell, =
the less it is worth. Harvard admits  like 2,000 students a year. If you co=
nsult for 3,000 students, no matter how good you are, some of them aren=E2=
=80=99t getting in.=C2=A0Really you want to charge an amount of money that =
is so absurd that most people won=E2=80=99t pay it, so that (1) you have ve=
ry few clients and don=E2=80=99t have to work too=C2=A0hard, (2) those few =
clients pay you a lot of money and (3) they get their money=E2=80=99s worth=
.
Also if you are in this business, your clients (I mean, the parents) will p=
robably come disproportionately from the financial industry, and=C2=A0they =
will understand this. Here is a fun   Bloomberg News story about Christophe=
r Rim, who runs a company called Command Education that is apparently quite=
