 $750,000. But some parents would, sensibly,=C2=A0rather pay more to get hi=
m to work less:
Rim said a parent at New York=E2=80=99s Trinity School =E2=80=94 a $64,000-=
a-year Ivy League-feeder =E2=80=94 once offered him $1.5 million if he woul=
d agree not to work with any of his child=E2=80=99s classmates (Rim decline=
d).
I mean of course he declined! That=E2=80=99s just twice his usual rate, and=
 surely he can get more than two clients a year from Trinity. There is some=
 number, though ($5 million?), at which=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s an interesting tr=
ade: For Rim, he=C2=A0gets most of his Trinity revenue with much less work =
(just the one kid), and for the parent, I mean,=C2=A0someone=C2=A0from Trin=
ity is going to get into Harvard =E2=80=94=C2=A0the competition is not quit=
e zero-sum but it is close =E2=80=94=C2=A0and kneecapping everyone else is =
at least as valuable as inflating your own kid=E2=80=99s resume. The parent=
