By the way, there is an analogous story early in Michael Lewis=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0Flash Boys. Spread Networks was building a very fast data line from New =
York to Chicago=C2=A0and selling space on the line to financial firms:
All its creators knew was that the Wall Street people who wanted it wanted =
it very badly =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also wanted to find ways for others not to=
 have it. In one of his first meetings with a big Wall Street firm, Spivey =
had told the firm=E2=80=99s boss the price of his line: $10.6 million plus =
costs if he paid up front, $20 million or so if he paid in installments. Th=
e boss said he=E2=80=99d like to go away and think about it. He returned wi=
th a single question: =E2=80=9CCan you double the price?=E2=80=9D
Having a fast connection between New York and Chicago, or a good high schoo=
l resume, is nothing. Having a=C2=A0faster=C2=A0connection between New York=
 and Chicago, or a=C2=A0better=C2=A0high school resume, is everything. It i=
s always good to be in a business where your customers beg you to take more=
 money to work less.

