isors] have consistently communicated that retaining the<span>=C2=A0</span>=
Company=E2=80=99s management is not a condition to acquiring the Company. H=
owever, deal certainty is.<span>=C2=A0</span>As [the Consortium] know[s] we=
ll from running [its] own asset management business, clients care<span>=C2=
=A0</span>about who is managing their money.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you might think that the board would try ve=
ry hard to find out if the clients would be okay with Weinstein running the=
ir money. =E2=80=9CGiven the large concentration of revenue run rate in a s=
mall number of clients, a small number of clients failing to provide consen=
t could result in a failure to satisfy the Consortium Client Consent Condit=
ion,=E2=80=9D says Sculptor, but that also makes the problem kind of easy: =
Just ask the small number of big clients =E2=80=9Chey would you be okay wit=
h the Weinstein deal?=E2=80=9D (Maybe ask Weinstein to waive the NDA first!=
) If they all say =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D then you take the Weinstein deal. I=
f they all say =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D then (1) you stick with the Rithm deal =
and (2) <em>you call Weinstein up and tell him that</em>. Presumably=C2=A0<=
em>he=C2=A0</em>doesn=E2=80=99t want to buy Sculptor if there are no client=
s left.=C2=A0<em>He=C2=A0</em>thinks he can keep the clients, but most hedg=
e fund managers are pretty confident. Maybe he=E2=80=99s wrong. But if he=
=E2=80=99s wrong you can find out and tell him!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weirdest thing about this deal is that Scu=
lptor does not seem to be doing that. It is sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0hinting =
at that? In a Sept. 5 meeting, the board =E2=80=9Cdiscussed with its adviso=
rs that=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0based on feedback from clients to the client re=
lations team, a number of clients of the Company had already raised concern=
