intermediaries, revenue run rate/client concentration, key-man provisions a=
nd redemption rights contained in certain client agreements, and certain fe=
edback received from clients relevant to the Consortium Client Consent Cond=
ition Risk analysis, (iii)=C2=A0reviewing the proposals from the Consortium=
 (and responses to clarifying questions received from the Consortium) and (=
iv) other publicly available information (collectively, the =E2=80=9CAssess=
ment Steps=E2=80=9D).</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What did the consultant come up with? Somethin=
g very odd:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Asset Management Consultant no=
ted that typical drivers of client loss following a change of control inclu=
de (i) departures of key persons and/or destabilization of an investment te=
am, (ii) material changes to the Investment Function and (iii) concerns abo=
ut overall firm governance and ownership.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? =E2=80=9CTypical drivers of client loss=
=E2=80=9D? Like, if I were on the board, here is the conversation I would w=
ant to have:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board: </strong>How many of our client=
s will leave if we sell to Boaz Weinstein?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Consultant:</strong> Like 60%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> How do you know?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Consultant:</strong> We asked them.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> Okay fine we=E2=80=99r=
e sticking with $11.15.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the conversation they apparently had i=
nstead:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> How many of our client=
s will leave if we sell to Boaz Weinstein?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Consultant:</strong> Typically when a =
hedge fund has a change of control, some number of clients leave due to div=
erse reasons including but not limited to departures of key persons, destab=
ilization of investment teams, material changes to the investment function =
and concerns about overall governance and ownership.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> I=E2=80=99m satisfied,=
 no further questions from me, let=E2=80=99s stick with $11.15.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The consultant didn=E2=80=99t answer the quest=
ion! Or, I mean,=C2=A0maybe it=C2=A0<em>did</em>, but Sculptor won=E2=80=99=
t say so in the proxy. I don=E2=80=99t understand it. Surely the whole ball=
game here is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Figure=C2=A0out how many of your clie=
nts would leave if you agreed to sell to Boaz Weinstein.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tell shareholders the answer.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For some reason Sculptor won=E2=80=99t do that=
!</p>
