<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about it is that a private eq=
uity firm is a conglomerate plus financial engineering. Traditionally, a co=
nglomerate is a big company that owns lots of more-or-less unrelated busine=
sses. Some of them will do well and others will do poorly, but the ones tha=
t are doing well can help support the ones that are doing poorly, and hopef=
ully most will do well and the overall company will make money. Meanwhile t=
he overall company is big and fairly stable (its bets are diversified), so =
it can borrow money cheaply, and it has talented managers who can make all =
of the component businesses work better.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A private equity=C2=A0fund also buys lots of m=
ore-or-less unrelated businesses, some of which will do well and others poo=
rly. The overall fund has talented managers who can supervise and optimize =
all of the businesses. But instead of borrowing money at the overall fund l=
evel, the=C2=A0fund keeps each of its unrelated businesses separate as a le=
gal and financial matter: Each business has its own balance sheet and borro=
ws its own money. And the businesses borrow a=C2=A0<em>lot=C2=A0</em>of mon=
ey: Private equity companies=C2=A0tend to run at higher leverage than tradi=
tional public conglomerates.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result of this is that the PE fund is a se=
ries of somewhat independent bets on different businesses, and each bet has=
 high variance: There is some chance that the bet will go to zero (the comp=
any is very levered, it fails, and the PE fund loses its entire investment)=
, and some chance that the bet will return 1,000% (the company is very leve=
red, it succeeds, and the PE fund gets back 10x its=C2=A0equity investment)=
. Whereas in a traditional conglomerate the bets have less variance and are=
 more likely to cancel each other out: Losses at one business are a drag on=
 the other businesses in a way that isn=E2=80=99t exactly true for a PE=C2=
=A0fund full of independent bankruptcy-remote companies.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA basket of options is worth more than an option on a ba=
sket,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/327=
50625.259424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
EtMTEtMTAvbWNraW5zZXktcGFydG5lci1zLWluc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy1zdHJhdGVneS13YXMtY=
mFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJj=
ZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4660ccb0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I sometimes say</a>; a PE fund is =
more like a basket of options, while a conglomerate where all the businesse=
s support one another is more like an option on a basket.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, once you own a bunch of com=
panies you don=E2=80=99t actually want to give up on the ones that are=C2=
=A0struggling. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32750625.259424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYmU5ZTA5NWYtNzFiOC00MD=
JmLWE0MDQtMTE3MmQ2ZGYxZmI3P3NoYXJlVHlwZT1ub25naWZ0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B1e9db5c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Financial Times reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Private equity firms have started to borrow ag=
ainst their funds to backstop overly indebted portfolio companies, a new fi=
nancial engineering tactic meant to cope with higher interest rates and a s=
lowdown in dealmaking.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The manoeuvres, which lenders have dubbed =E2=
=80=9Cdefending the portfolio=E2=80=9D, have cropped up as many older priva=
te equity funds run low on cash just as the companies they own struggle wit=
h their own debt loads.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buyout firms have turned to so-called net asse=
t value (NAV) loans, which use a fund=E2=80=99s investment assets as collat=
eral. They are deploying the proceeds to help pay down the debts of individ=
ual companies held by the fund, according to private equity executives and =
senior bankers and lenders to the industry.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By securing a loan against a larger pool of as=
sets, private equity firms are able to negotiate lower borrowing costs than=
 would be possible if the portfolio company attempted to obtain a loan on i=
ts own.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last month Vista Equity Partners, a private eq=
uity investor focused on the technology industry, used a NAV loan against o=
ne of its funds to help raise $1bn that it then pumped into financial techn=
ology company Finastra, according to five people familiar with the matter.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Limited liability at the company level is an e=
ssential part of the private equity model<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>: You borrow a lot at every company, and the ones that don=E2=80=99t wo=
rk out you cut loose; their creditors take losses so you can protect the re=
st of your portfolio. But in practice you will be tempted not to cut any co=
mpanies loose, to use the winners to prop up the losers and try to rescue t=
hem.</p>
