<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say that you are very, very, ver=
y good at getting high school students into elite colleges. If someone hand=
s you a mediocre ninth grader, in three years you can hand them back a stud=
ent with, say, a 50% chance of getting into Harvard. This is a service that=
 a lot of people want, and that not a lot of people can provide. How should=
 you price it?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One answer might be =E2=80=9Ccharge a whole lo=
t, and then sell it to as many people as can afford to pay.=E2=80=9D Anothe=
r=C2=A0answer might be =E2=80=9Cprice discriminate as much as possible=E2=
=80=9D: Get the parents=E2=80=99 financial information, charge the really r=
ich ones $5 million, charge less rich ones less, and do some pro bono consu=
lting for poor but worthy candidates.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a flaw with these answers. The mo=
re of this service you sell, the less it is worth. Harvard admits <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32750625.259424/aHR0cHM6L=
y9jb2xsZWdlLmhhcnZhcmQuZWR1L2FkbWlzc2lvbnMvYWRtaXNzaW9ucy1zdGF0aXN0aWNz/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9790330d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> like 2,000 students a year</a>. If=
 you consult for 3,000 students, no matter how good you are, some of them a=
ren=E2=80=99t getting in.=C2=A0Really you want to charge an amount of money=
 that is so absurd that most people won=E2=80=99t pay it, so that (1) you h=
ave very few clients and don=E2=80=99t have to work too=C2=A0hard, (2) thos=
e few clients pay you a lot of money and (3) they get their money=E2=80=99s=
 worth.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also if you are in this business, your clients=
 (I mean, the parents) will probably come disproportionately from the finan=
cial industry, and=C2=A0<em>they will understand this</em>. Here is a fun <=
