e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg News story</a> about Chr=
istopher Rim, who runs a company called Command Education that is apparentl=
y quite good at getting high school students into fancy colleges. His rack =
rate is $750,000. But some parents would, sensibly,=C2=A0rather pay more to=
 get him to work less:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rim said a parent at New York=E2=
=80=99s Trinity School =E2=80=94 a $64,000-a-year Ivy League-feeder =E2=80=
=94 once offered him $1.5 million if he would agree not to work with any of=
 his child=E2=80=99s classmates (Rim declined).</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean of course he declined! That=E2=80=99s j=
ust twice his usual rate, and surely he can get more than two clients a yea=
r from Trinity. There is some number, though ($5 million?), at which=C2=A0i=
t=E2=80=99s an interesting trade: For Rim, he=C2=A0gets most of his Trinity=
 revenue with much less work (just the one kid), and for the parent, I mean=
,=C2=A0<em>someone=C2=A0</em>from Trinity is going to get into Harvard =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the competition is not quite zero-sum but it is close =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and kneecapping everyone else is at least as valuable as inflating yo=
ur own kid=E2=80=99s resume. The parent was on to something here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, there is an analogous story early =
in Michael Lewis=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
